<h1>@HI{{koto ga dekiru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{@EM{{ga dekiru}}}}
<li> @Vru{{}} @HI{{@EM{{koto ga dekiru}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
These two sentence patterns express an ability or possibility.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{dekiru}} is the <a href="grammar-verb-formation-potential.html">potential</a> form of @HI{{suru}}
and means "can" or "able to".
</p>

<p>
Nouns used in this sentence pattern are mostly those which indicate an action, such as skiing, dancing
or playing a sport.
</p>

<p>
When a verb is used to describe an ability or possibility, the dictionary form is nominalised by
<a href="grammar-koto-nominaliser.html">@HI{{koto}}</a> and it is then used as the noun part of the
sentence pattern above.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha @KJ{{day^book^word}}ga dekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller can speak Japanese.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha @KJ{{sino-^character}}wo@KJ{{read}}mu koto ga dekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller can read kanji.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

